\section{Introduction}
Filled skutterudite compounds represent a wide, interesting class of thermoelectric materials. They attract attention by combination of two contrasting physical properties: high electrical conductivity, comparable to that of the narrow band gap semiconductors, and a low thermal conductivity similar to the glasses ~\cite{SLK94, Sales96, SLK95}. A myriad of interesting transport properties has been observed in the filled skutterudites: metal-insulator transitions, conventional and unconventional superconductivity, heavy-fermion behavior, magnetic ordering ~\cite{Shirotani97, Bauer02, Sales03, Bauer04, Xing15}. Recent studies of these compounds reveal a strong dependency of these parameters on the structure and doping by rare-earth atoms \cite{Sales96}. A comprehensive understanding of physics behind the transport properties of filled skutterudites requires an insight on structure, its elastic response of unfilled framework structure to stresses and strains induced by doping \cite{Sales03}.\\
The framework of the filled skutterudites is built by parent compound, binary skutterudite $OMX_3$ with $O$, $M$ and $X$ being a vacancy, a d-metal, and a pnictogen atom, respectively. At ambient pressure the structure of the framework is cubic of type $CoAs_3$ with the space group $Im\overline{3}$ (\#204) and 8 molecules per unit cell. Each unit cell has 2 atoms of sort $M$ residing in the positions 8c, 6 atoms of sort $X$ occupying  the positions 24g, and 2 vacancies which are located in the positions 2a ~\cite{Sales96, SLK95}.  In the filled skutterudites, the vacancies are typically filled by rare-earth atoms which 'rattle' around the equilibrium positions and scatter the phonons, thus reducing thermal conductivity ~\cite{Sales96, SLK95, Nolas98}.\\
At present the most studied skutterudites have their frameworks built by Co$_{4}$Sb$_{12}$ polyanion. However, only a limited degree of filling can be achieved for this framework ~\cite{Sales96, Nolas98}. The recent study has demonstrated that substitution of Co by Fe increases the upper limit for filling fraction \cite{Sales00}. Notably that Fe$_{4}$Sb$_{12}$ with 716 electrons/unit cell and Co$_{4}$Sb$_{12}$ with 720 electrons/unit cell can be considered as almost isoelectronic compounds but FeSb$_3$ demonstrates smaller average phonon group velocity and phonon softening compared to CoSb$_3$, thus promises lower thermal conductivity\cite{Anne11, Pera15}. The increased filling fraction and the later observation raised the application potential of Fe$_{x}$Co$_{x-4}$Sb$_{12}$ and Fe$_{4}$Sb$_{12}$  and stimulated synthesis attempts further. \\
Interestingly, the parent compound FeSb$_3$ has not been fully studied yet owning to that the synthesis became possible only recently ~\cite{Williams01, Anne11, Daniel15}. To the best of our knowledge, the elastic properties of FeSb$_3$  have not been characterized under high-pressure yet. They are, however, of great importance as they shed light on structure stiffness. An enhanced stiffness of an unfilled skutterudite indicates that its framework may accommodate larger atoms without affecting structural integrity \cite{Anderson95}.\\
Here we report on a high-pressure X-ray diffraction study of CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$ at the similar quasi-hydrostatic conditions. The results allow us to quantify compression of the materials, measure their bulk modulus at ambient and high pressures. Moreover, the obtained data provide access to the structural stability and heat transport parameters of the compounds.\\
With respect to the high pressure behavior of CoSb$_3$, we discuss the problem of the 'self-insertion'  \cite{Kraemer07, Matsui12}. This effect is the pressure induced displacement of the $X$ atoms from framework 24g positions into vacant 2a sites. Self-insertion process can lead to formation of a new interesting thermoelectric compounds, e.g. Sb$_x$CoSb$_{3-x}$ in case of CoSb$_3$. Indeed, it was demonstrated recently that the skutterudite Sb$_x$CoSb$_{3-x}$ has an increased $ZT$ figure of merit compared to that of the parent compound\cite{Fugi14, Miotto11}. Thus, an understanding of the self-insertion effect is the key for improvement of performance of this thermoelectric material. In addition, we note that the previous studies of parent CoSb$_3$ \cite{Kraemer07, Matsui12} were carried out at non-hydrostatic conditions and the equation of state as well as the understanding on physics behind the 'self-insertion' should be revisited.

\section{Experimental aspects}
The FeSb$_3$ sample has been produced by elemental modulated reactant method (EMRM)\cite{Williams01, Anne11} in a form of thin films. The samples have been scratched from the substrate and grounded to a fine powder with grain size smaller than 10 $\mu$m. In case of FeSb$_3$ the sample was a mix of FeSb$_3$ and Si powders. Si additive was used as a internal calibrant for pressure and temperature in this case. CoSb$_3$ sample has been produced by chemical synthesis (please check either that is correct) and grounded to a fine powder.\\
We used symmetric diamond anvil cells (DAC) of Mao-type with 300 $\mu$m culets and Rhenium gaskets to constrain the samples and the pressure medium in each run. The gasket plate was pre-indented to a thickness of about 30 $\mu$m, and a hole of about 150 $\mu$m in diameter has been drilled by electric discharge machine. The ruby spheres have been loaded into the sample enclosure in the DAC together with Ne pressure medium and the pressure was measured from the shift of the luminescence line of the ruby spheres using standard calibration procedures after Ref.\cite{Mao86} in the pressure range atm-8 GPa and after Ref.\cite{Dewaele08} at the higher pressures.
\\
 Our experiment has been performed at P02.2 extreme conditions beamline of the PETRA III light source \cite{Liermann10}. The experimental pressure range was atm-39.6 GPa for CoSb$_3$ and atm-42.4 GPa for FeSb$_3$ and the wavelength of 0.2893 \r{A} was employed. In addition to the high pressure data we have measured ambient pressure lattice parameters of FeSb$_3$ at the high resolution powder diffraction beamline P02.1 of the PETRA III light source using the wavelength  of 0.2078 \r{A}.  The 2D-detector (Perkin-Eimer XRD1621) with the pixel size 200 $\mu$m has been used in both experiments while the distance from sample to detector was 518.633 and 2061.472 mm in the experiments at the high-pressures and in the experiments at ambient pressure, respectively. For the high-pressure experiments the beam was focused by compound refractive lenses to the size approximately 3x8 $\mu$m$^2$.
The obtained two-dimensional patterns were integrated by Fit2D program \cite{Hammers97} and the received one-dimensional $\Theta-2\Theta$ patterns were analyzed by JANA program \cite{Petricek14} within the le Bail data analysis. Good quality of ambient pressure data allowed us to carry out Rietveld analysis.\\
