\section{Results}
\subsection{CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$ at atmospheric pressure}
The crystal structure of the both compounds is described by $Im\overline{3}$ (\# 204) space group at ambient pressure. For CoSb$_3$ we observe an excellent agreement between V$_0$ obtained by us and the values reported in the literature (see Table \ref{Table1}). Refinement of the diffraction pattern for FeSb$_3$ (s. Fig \ref{diffrfe}) delivers V$_0$ much lower than that given in the literature (see Table \ref{Table1}). We strongly believe that this prominent discrepancy can be attributed to the differences in the material preparation procedures. In the works \cite{Hornb97,Anne11,Daniel15} FeSb$_3$  was in the form a thin film deposited on substrates which is easy to bend, while in our study the material was in a form of powder and has undergone substantial grinding in the agate mortar. Thus the material was less affected by additional strains attributed to the sample-substrate interface in our case. The work \cite{Daniel15} gives the lattice constant lower than in the Ref. \cite{Anne11}. The similarly lower lattice constant was obtained in the work with FeSb$_3$ thin film annealed at 250$^o$C for 7 hours (s. Table \ref{Table1}) \cite{Hornb97}. Therefore, the hypothesis about bending of the substrate in the works \cite{Anne11, Daniel15} can be reliable. The effect of the strain can indeed explain a strong scatter of V$_0$ reported in literature \cite{Hornb97,Anne11,Daniel15} and therefore the observation should be taken into account as measurements of the elastic properties of the strained thin films are by default modified and do not represent bulk properties of the material.

