\subsection{CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$ in the pressure range atm-34 GPa}
In the Figure \ref{pv} we show experimental data on material volume as a function of pressure. The relative deviations Rp and wRp between the experimental and the modeled pattern are not higher than 0.7 and 1.2, respectively, at the pressures below 34.4 GPa for CoSb$_3$ and below 14 GPa for FeSb$_3$.

\begin{figure}[ht]
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{eos.eps}
\caption{\label{pv}Volume of the unit cell for CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$ as a function of pressure. The red and blue curves are the Birch-Murnaghan equations of state for CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$, respectively. The green stars show structural transitions of Si admixture in FeSb$_3$\cite{Ducl90}}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[ht]
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{vbyv.eps}
\caption{\label{volvol}Pressure dependency of volume of the FeSb$_3$ unit cell. Data are normalized on the volumes of the CoSb$_3$ unit cell calculated from EoS. The green stars indicate structural transitions of Si in FeSb$_3$\cite{Ducl90}}
\end{figure}

The experimental P-V data can be approximated by EoS in the pressure range atm-34 GPa for CoSb$_3$ and atm-14 GPa for FeSb$_3$. The fit parameters V$_0$, $B_0$, and $B_0^\prime$ are shown in the Table \ref{Table2}. Here, the reduced $\chi^2$ statistical test criterium of the goodness of fits is 0.0689 for the both fits.
The fit of the experimental data for FeSb$_3$ is possible for the pressure range atm-42.4 GPa, however, the reduced $\chi^2$ for this fit will be 0.1872. A poor quality of data due to the silicon admixture in FeSb$_3$ is the reason of the increased error of the fit. At the pressures 11-15 GPa silicon structure changes from cubic to tetragonal\cite{Hanfl99, Hu86} and additional reflections from silicon appear in the diffraction patterns at the pressures higher than 14.7 GPa, overlaping the reflections of FeSb$_3$ and impeding the determination of the lattice constant. \\
The bulk modulus of CoSb$_3$ has been determined from the fit as 95(5) GPa. This value is in a very good agreement with the literature data 93(6) GPa\cite{Kraemer05, Kraemer07}. Bulk modulus for FeSb$_3$ was obtained as 86(4) GPa, being about 30\% higher compared to the literature value \cite{Anne11} obtained indirectly.\\
The F-f plot for CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$ is shown in the Figure \ref{ff}. For CoSb$_3$, we observe that the normalized stress F is nearly constant in the pressure range atm-34.4 GPa. This allows us to state that CoSb$_3$ skutterudite does not undergo structural transitions up to the pressure 34 GPa which is higher than the values reported previously \cite{Kraemer07, Matsui12}.\\
For FeSb$_3$ we observe as least 4 knot points in the F-f plot: at 14, 21, 30, and 34 GPa. Here, it is notable that F is constant in the pressure ranges atm-14, 21-30, 34-42 GPa. Constant value of F shows that during fit the $B_0^\prime$=4 and a change of structure is not probable. The positive slope of F indicates a possible structural change in the pressure ranges 14-21 and 30-34 GPa. In the range 14-21 GPa the change is probably reasoned by non-hydrostatic condition due to the structural transition of the Si admixture. Indeed, the width of the reflection (1 0 3) in FeSb$_3$ has a monotonic increase at the pressures higher than 30 GPa (Fig.\ref{refl}). This fact can be a sign of increased stress and most unlikely a change in the structure as it is the case in CoSb$_3$ (see the next section). The increased stress is most probable due to the non-hydrostatic conditions in this pressure range.

