\subsection{CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$ in the pressure range 34-40 GPa}

There is an interesting change in the diffraction pattern of CoSb$_3$ at 34.4 GPa (Fig. \ref{diffr}). The widths of the reflections increase abruptly at this pressure (Fig. \ref{refl}). Furthermore, it is clearly seen that the (2 2 4) reflection do split at the pressure 34.4 GPa (Fig. \ref{diffr}).
We note that the structural change of CoSb$_3$ observed by us has been seen before \cite{Kraemer07, Matsui12}, however, the splitting of the reflections was probably not resolved in the works \cite{Kraemer07, Matsui12}. In that studies the pressure point of the change was predicted to reside between 20 GPa and 35 GPa \cite{Kraemer07, Matsui12}. Neon used in our study provides better hydrostatic conditions in the sample enclosure upon increase of the pressure, in contrast to methanol-ethanol and methanol-ethanol-water pressure media \cite{Batchelder67, Hazen84} used in the works \cite{Kraemer07, Matsui12}. The usage of neon as pressure medium allowed us to determine the pressure point more precisely.\\
Interestingly, we observe a change in diffraction pattern of CoSb$_3$ at the pressure 34.4 GPa, namely several reflections become broader or split (Fig. \ref{diffr}). Recently, it has been shown that the abrupt increase of the widths of reflections is a typical evidence of a structural transition in the pnictide compounds with similar structure\cite{Mart11, MCG08, Mart09, Marty11}. The abrupt increase of the widths (Fig. \ref{refl}) and the splitting of the reflections (Fig. \ref{diffr}) can thus be interpreted as the marks of a structural transition. The reason of the transition is not clear for us, it could probably be induced by non-hydrostacity and the uniaxial compression of the sample at this pressure.

\begin{figure}[ht]
\includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{twotheta.eps}
\caption{\label{diffr}Evolution of diffraction patterns with pressure for CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$. Green and pink stars show peaks from Si phases}
\end{figure}

No significant changes were observed in the diffraction pattern for FeSb$_3$ (Fig. \ref{diffr}) up to 40 GPa, although the width of the (1 0 3) reflection increases monotonically in the pressure range 30-40 GPa. Such increase is characteristic for the appearance of mechanical stress in the sample and most unlikely for a structure transition. The increased stress and the shapes of the reflections (Fig. \ref{diffr}) can be the signs of non-hydrostatic compression of FeSb$_3$ which starts to appear at 30 GPa and becomes more pronounced at 37 GPa, probably due to the impact of the Si admixture.

\section{Conclusions}

As a conclusion, we measured compressibility of the unfilled CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$ skutterudites by high-pressure synchrotron X-ray diffraction. Ne pressure medium provided conditions close to hydrostatic.
The experimental data have been approximated by third order Birch-Murnaghan isothermal equations of state in the pressure ranges atm-34 GPa for CoSb$_3$ and atm-14 GPa for FeSb$_3$. Notably, the equation of state for FeSb$_3$ has been received for the first time. The bulk moduli have been derived as 95(5) GPa and 86(4) GPa for CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$, respectively. The bulk modulus of FeSb$_3$ is about 30\% higher compared to the literature value obtained indirectly. No significant difference in the volumes of the unit cells of CoSb$_3$ and FeSb$_3$ was observed in the pressure range atm-14 GPa.
The anomaly in the diffraction pattern of CoSb$_3$ have been observed at the pressures 34.4-39.6 GPa. The anomaly is most probably due to a change in the crystal structure induced by the uniaxial compression of the sample. We note that the anomaly was not observed in the diffraction pattern of FeSb$_3$ up to 40 GPa, however, the compressibility data might be influenced by the non-hydrostacity in the pressure range 30-40 GPa.













































